               <msContents class="thematic">
                  <summary>This manuscript contains a commentary on the book of Aphorisms attributed to <persName type="standard" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/287984736" key="person_287984736">Hippocrates</persName>.</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="MS_Petermann_II_233-item1">
                     <author key="person_4405945">
                        <persName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/4405945" type="aut">Ibn Abī Ṣādiq‏ابن أبي صادق</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="en" type="desc" key="work_7754">Commentary on Hippocratic Aphorisms</title>
                     <title xml:lang="ar" key="work_7754">شرح فصول أبقراط</title>
                     <title xml:lang="en" type="alt" key="work_7754">Sharḥ Fuṣūl Abuqrāṭ</title>
                     <note>Original manuscript in Berlin State Library.</note>
                     <note>This is a thematically arranged commentary (see <ref type="article">Pormann, Joosse 2012, pp. 221-222</ref>). The introduction begins on f. 1b and the table of contents is in ff. 2b-3a. The beginning of each bāb is as follows: Bab 1: f. 3a; Bab 2: f. 8b; Bab 3: f. 18a; Bab 4: f. 32a; Bab 5: f. 37a; Bab 6: f. 46b; Bab 7: f. 90a (“On diseases afflicting women”); Bab 8: f. 101b; Bab 9: f. 109b; Bab 10: f. 111a; Bab 11: f. 117a; Bab 12: f. 118b; Bab 13: f. 120b; Bab 14: f. 122b ("On crises and their days, and the purges that happen in them and the symptoms that occur during [the crisis]"); Bab 15: f. 130a; Bab 16: f. 136a; Bab 17: f. 137a; Bab 18: f. 138a (On drink); Bab 19: f. 139b; Bab 20: f. 143b. And conclusion (khātima) is on f. 148b. The copy is complete.</note>
                     <listBibl>
                        <bibl>
                           <persName key="person_27218796" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/27218796">Ahlwardt, Wilhelm</persName>, <biblScope unit="pages">vil.5, pp. 495-6</biblScope>
                        </bibl>
                     </listBibl>
                     <textLang mainLang="ar">Arabic</textLang>
                  </msItem>
